death in the andes archaeological discovery of an historical mystery page 1 2011 2012 clas lecture series presents death in the andes archaeological discovery of an historical mystery john rick associate professor of anthropology stanford university the surprising discovery of approximately 36 human skeletons of relatively recent historical age in the 3000 year old monumental site of chavin de huantar in the north central peruvian highlands has provoked the inevitable investigation into the identity of the individuals and the reason for their death factoring in the ages sexes physical condition burial accompaniments grave postures grave distribution and form and other attributes for a location of no known historical cemetery activity has started to give some answers to these questions how a group of people of at least this size could die in an apparent event but be lost to history in a small andean town such as chavin suggests very special circumstances and there are striking bits of evidence of violence and disrespectful treatment of the dead that suggest a conflict based incident evidence currently points to the cruel and violence wracked war of the pacific period of the early 1880's as the likely cause of the deaths as peruvian and chilean armies streamed through the chavin area i explore the marshalling of many lines of circumstantial and contingent evidence to illustrate a lost chapter of andean history january 10 2012 12 15 1 05 pm center for latin american studies 582 alvarado row light lunch served
